# fusion-box wine patch 0006
# Virtual subsurface for Qt6 WS_CHILD widgets that paint into the toplevel's
# GDI buffer ("GDI-buffer slice promotion").
#
# Iteration 2 (2026-07-02): freeze vsub commits during toplevel resize.
# Fixes intermittent white/black flash of the nav toolbar during window
# resize / maximize. Qt sends transient WAYLAND_WindowPosChanged events
# for the toolbar HWND with intermediate positions (e.g. mid-toplevel
# instead of bottom-center) while mid-relayout; empirically these
# transients survive 5+ consecutive frames so per-child streak-based
# hysteresis is unreliable. Instead we track the TOPLEVEL's own size
# across parent commits and skip the vsub commit loop until the toplevel
# size has been stable for 3 consecutive commits. During the freeze,
# vsubs retain their last-attached buffer per wayland protocol, so the
# toolbar visually stays at the last stable position until layout
# settles. See docs/observed-issues.md patch 0006 entry for the trace
# analysis that led to this iteration.
#
# Bug:
# Fusion 360's center-bottom navigation toolbar (orbit/pan/zoom/fit/etc.) is a
# Qt6 WS_CHILD widget (`Qt683QWindowIcon`) that paints its pixels into the
# parent toplevel's GDI window_surface - it does NOT own a DXVK swapchain.
# Sibling Qt6 widgets (the modeling viewport, ribbon, etc.) DO own DXVK
# swapchains, each presented through its own `wayland_client_surface`
# attached as a sibling subsurface of the main toplevel. Per the Wayland
# subsurface protocol, the parent's buffer is always at the BOTTOM of the
# composite tree - every subsurface renders above it. The nav toolbar's
# pixels live in main's buffer, so they're inherently underneath the
# viewport's white swapchain. No subsurface z-order shuffle among main's
# siblings can lift main's own buffer above its children.
#
# This was previously documented in docs/observed-issues.md as "no
# winewayland.drv-only fix exists" - the Qt6 paint-target / DXVK
# render-target architectural mismatch. See docs/bottom-toolbar-burial.md
# for the full investigation.
#
# Fix (Path 2 from bottom-toolbar-burial.md, "GDI-buffer slice promotion"):
# For each Qt6 WS_CHILD widget that (a) is visible with a non-empty rect,
# (b) is small enough to be toolbar-like (h<=50, w<=1000), (c) does NOT own
# its own client_surface, and (d) lives under a TOPLEVEL-role
# wayland_surface, synthesize a wl_subsurface attached to the toplevel.
# This "virtual" subsurface owns no buffer of its own; on every parent GDI
# commit, attach the parent's wl_buffer to the virtual subsurface with a
# wp_viewport_set_source crop matching the child's screen-rect-within-
# toplevel. The virtual subsurface lands above sibling DXVK
# client_subsurfaces by Wayland creation-order rule, so the cropped toolbar
# pixels render on top.
#
# Why this works architecturally:
# Qt6's own native QtWaylandClient platform plugin uses exactly this pattern:
# it extracts sub-rects from a parent's SHM backing buffer and presents
# them through the child's own wl_subsurface
# (qtbase/src/plugins/platforms/wayland/qwaylandshmbackingstore.cpp:301-316).
# When Qt runs under wine + winewayland, however, Qt's *Win32* QPA plugin
# (qwindows.dll) doesn't request per-WS_CHILD GDI window_surfaces - children
# share the parent's HDC. Wine's gate at window.c:583 (the `if (!surface)`
# branch in WAYLAND_WindowPosChanged) destroys any existing wayland_surface
# when win32u passes a NULL window_surface, and short-circuits before
# wayland_win_data_create_wayland_surface ever fires. So no wayland_surface
# ever exists for the nav toolbar's HWND.
#
# Empirical verification of the underlying primitive (2026-06-09):
# debug/wine-tests/shared-buffer-test/ - a pure wayland-client program (no
# wine) that exercises "parent SHM buffer + N viewport-cropped subsurfaces
# + opaque sibling subsurface between them". KDE Plasma 6 KWin composites
# this arrangement correctly on NVIDIA Open driver 610.43.02.
#
# Empirical verification on Fusion 360 (2026-06-09):
# Nav toolbar renders at correct position over the modeling viewport.
# Hover triggers tooltips (input passes through to Win32 via the empty
# input region on the virtual subsurface). Clicks open submenus correctly.
# Works across window resize/move (the commit hook recomputes the
# child-local rect on every parent commit).
#
# Strictness of the gate (deliberately restrictive - earlier permissive
# version over-created subsurfaces for every visible WS_CHILD and broke
# the UI):
#   - HWND has WS_CHILD style.
#   - HWND is visible (WS_VISIBLE) with non-zero rect.
#   - data->client_surface == NULL (no DXVK swapchain of its own).
#   - HWND's rect is "toolbar-like": height <= 50, width <= 1000.
#     (Fusion's nav toolbar is 239x24. Full-content panels are excluded.)
#   - Toplevel ancestor's wayland_surface exists with TOPLEVEL role and
#     valid wl_surface (so the wl_subsurface_get_subsurface call won't
#     fail with "no parent").
#
# Open work / future refinements:
#   - Empty input region means clicks fall through to the toplevel's
#     wl_surface, which wine then routes to the correct child HWND via
#     win32 cursor coords. Works in practice; cursor-shape updates on
#     hover are missing (separate bug class, not in scope).
#   - The size gate is a heuristic. A future revision should base it on
#     "overlaps a sibling whose client_surface is non-NULL" instead -
#     more principled, less risk of false positive on similarly-sized
#     widgets that don't need promotion.
#   - The commit hook fires on every parent GDI flush. For widgets whose
#     rect hasn't changed, the position+viewport+attach sequence is
#     mostly redundant. Cheap to skip if needed.
#
# Apply from the wine source root: `patch -p1 < this-file`. Depends on
# patches 0001-0005 (line offsets assume all five are applied).
#
# Author: fusion-box (claude-code session, with Barrett Otte)
#
